{
  "format": "tiptap/v1",
  "doc": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "From Implicit Fields to Explicit Gaussians"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "NeRF represents a scene implicitly: to render a single pixel, hundreds of MLP queries march along a ray. Rendering a 1080p frame can require 500 million network evaluations — which is why NeRF renders at one frame per minute. 3D Gaussian Splatting (3DGS, Kerbl et al. 2023) takes the opposite approach: represent the scene "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "explicitly"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " as millions of coloured, semi-transparent 3D Gaussian blobs. Rendering becomes a rasterisation problem — project the Gaussians onto the screen, sort them by depth, and alpha-composite them. Modern GPUs do this at "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "100–200 fps at 1080p"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ", while achieving higher PSNR than most NeRF variants."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "3DGS rendering pipeline (left), adaptive density control (right), and comparison table with NeRF variants (bottom)"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Gaussian Primitive Representation"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Each Gaussian primitive stores five properties:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Position μ ∈ ℝ³."
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " The Gaussian centre in world space. Initialised from a COLMAP sparse point cloud."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Covariance Σ ∈ ℝ³ˣ³ (symmetric, positive semi-definite)."
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " Controls the shape and orientation of the blob. Parameterised as Σ = RSS^T R^T where R is a rotation quaternion and S = diag(s₁, s₂, s₃) is a scaling matrix — guaranteeing positive semi-definiteness during gradient descent."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Opacity o ∈ (0, 1)."
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " Base transparency; stored as logit and passed through sigmoid."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Spherical harmonic (SH) coefficients."
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " Up to degree 3 (48 coefficients per colour channel) encode view-dependent colour, capturing specular highlights without a separate view-direction MLP."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "3D to 2D Gaussian Projection"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "To rasterise, each 3D Gaussian is projected to a 2D screen-space Gaussian. Given view matrix W and projective Jacobian J (the local affine approximation of the perspective projection):"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "\\boldsymbol{\\mu}' = \\pi(\\mathbf{W}\\boldsymbol{\\mu}) \\qquad \\boldsymbol{\\Sigma}' = \\mathbf{J}\\mathbf{W}\\boldsymbol{\\Sigma}\\mathbf{W}^\\top\\mathbf{J}^\\top"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The contribution of a 2D Gaussian to pixel x′ is:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "\\alpha_i(\\mathbf{x}') = o_i \\cdot \\exp\\!\\left(-\\tfrac{1}{2}(\\mathbf{x}'-\\boldsymbol{\\mu}_i')^\\top\\boldsymbol{\\Sigma}_i'^{-1}(\\mathbf{x}'-\\boldsymbol{\\mu}_i')\\right)"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Gaussians that project to radius < 3σ of pixel x′ contribute nothing and are skipped. The final pixel colour is front-to-back alpha compositing over all overlapping Gaussians, sorted by depth:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "C(\\mathbf{x}') = \\sum_{i \\in \\mathcal{N}} \\mathbf{c}_i \\,\\alpha_i \\prod_{j < i}(1-\\alpha_j)"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Training and Adaptive Density Control"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Training optimises all Gaussian parameters with Adam. The loss is a combination of L1 photometric loss and the D-SSIM structural term:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "\\mathcal{L} = (1-\\lambda)\\,\\mathcal{L}_1 + \\lambda\\,\\mathcal{L}_{\\text{D-SSIM}} \\qquad \\lambda = 0.2"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Beyond gradient descent, 3DGS uses "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "adaptive density control"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " every 100 iterations to reshape the Gaussian cloud:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Clone"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — if a small Gaussian (small scale) has a large positional gradient, the region needs more coverage. Duplicate and push copies apart."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Split"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — if a large Gaussian has a large positional gradient, it's over-covering a high-detail region. Replace with two smaller Gaussians sampled from the original distribution."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Prune"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — remove Gaussians where o < 0.005 (transparent floaters) or where the world-space scale exceeds a scene-size threshold."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Opacity reset"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — every 3,000 iterations, reset all opacities to near-zero so the network re-learns which Gaussians genuinely contribute, preventing saturation."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Training with gsplat"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The original 3DGS CUDA rasterizer is wrapped by Nerfstudio and the standalone "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "gsplat"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " library. The snippet below shows the core forward pass with gsplat:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# pip install gsplat\nimport torch\nimport numpy as np\nfrom gsplat import rasterization\n\n\nclass GaussianScene(torch.nn.Module):\n    \"\"\"\n    Learnable 3D Gaussian scene with N primitives.\n    \"\"\"\n    def __init__(self, init_pts: torch.Tensor):\n        super().__init__()\n        N = len(init_pts)\n        self.means   = torch.nn.Parameter(init_pts.clone())         # (N, 3)\n        self.quats   = torch.nn.Parameter(                          # (N, 4) unit quaternion\n            torch.zeros(N, 4).scatter_(1, torch.zeros(N, 1, dtype=torch.long), 1.0)\n        )\n        self.scales  = torch.nn.Parameter(torch.full((N, 3), -3.0)) # (N, 3) log-scale\n        self.opacities = torch.nn.Parameter(torch.zeros(N))         # (N,) logit-opacity\n        # SH degree-0 (diffuse colour only); full SH would be (N, K, 3) with K=(deg+1)²\n        self.sh_coeffs = torch.nn.Parameter(torch.zeros(N, 1, 3))   # (N, 1, 3)\n\n    def forward(\n        self,\n        viewmats:   torch.Tensor,   # (B, 4, 4) world-to-camera\n        Ks:         torch.Tensor,   # (B, 3, 3) intrinsics\n        width:      int,\n        height:     int,\n        sh_degree:  int = 0,\n    ) -> torch.Tensor:\n        renders, alphas, meta = rasterization(\n            means       = self.means,\n            quats       = torch.nn.functional.normalize(self.quats, dim=-1),\n            scales      = torch.exp(self.scales),\n            opacities   = torch.sigmoid(self.opacities),\n            colors      = self.sh_coeffs,\n            viewmats    = viewmats,\n            Ks          = Ks,\n            width       = width,\n            height      = height,\n            sh_degree   = sh_degree,\n        )\n        return renders  # (B, H, W, 3) in [0, 1]\n\n\ndef train_gaussian_splatting(\n    images:   list,     # list of (H, W, 3) float32 tensors in [0,1]\n    c2w_mats: list,     # list of (4, 4) camera-to-world matrices\n    intrinsics: torch.Tensor,  # (3, 3)\n    init_pts: torch.Tensor,    # (N, 3) from COLMAP sparse cloud\n    n_iters: int = 30_000,\n):\n    device = \"cuda\"\n    scene = GaussianScene(init_pts).to(device)\n\n    optimizer = torch.optim.Adam([\n        {\"params\": scene.means,     \"lr\": 1.6e-4},\n        {\"params\": scene.quats,     \"lr\": 1e-3},\n        {\"params\": scene.scales,    \"lr\": 5e-3},\n        {\"params\": scene.opacities, \"lr\": 5e-2},\n        {\"params\": scene.sh_coeffs, \"lr\": 2.5e-3},\n    ])\n\n    H, W = images[0].shape[:2]\n    K = intrinsics.unsqueeze(0).to(device)  # (1, 3, 3)\n\n    for step in range(n_iters):\n        idx   = np.random.randint(len(images))\n        gt    = images[idx].to(device)                   # (H, W, 3)\n        c2w   = c2w_mats[idx].to(device)\n        w2c   = torch.linalg.inv(c2w).unsqueeze(0)       # (1, 4, 4)\n\n        rendered = scene(w2c, K, W, H)                   # (1, H, W, 3)\n        rendered = rendered[0]                           # (H, W, 3)\n\n        l1   = torch.abs(rendered - gt).mean()\n        # D-SSIM: simplified as (1 - SSIM) / 2; use torchmetrics in production\n        loss = 0.8 * l1   # + 0.2 * d_ssim(rendered, gt)\n\n        optimizer.zero_grad()\n        loss.backward()\n        optimizer.step()\n\n        if step % 10_000 == 0:\n            print(f\"step {step:6d} | loss {loss.item():.5f} | \"\n                  f\"N_gaussians {len(scene.means):,}\")\n\n    return scene"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Nerfstudio / CLI Workflow"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "bash"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# Step 1: prepare images → COLMAP poses\nns-process-data images --data ./photos/ --output-dir ./scene/\n\n# Step 2: train 3DGS (~30 min on RTX 3090)\nns-train splatfacto --data ./scene/ --max-num-iterations 30000\n\n# Step 3: render orbit video\nns-render camera-path \\\n  --load-config outputs/scene/splatfacto/2024-01-01/config.yml \\\n  --camera-path-filename scene/camera_paths/orbit.json \\\n  --output-path orbit.mp4\n\n# Step 4: export PLY for use in Blender / Unity / game engine\nns-export gaussian-splat \\\n  --load-config outputs/scene/splatfacto/2024-01-01/config.yml \\\n  --output-dir exports/ \\\n  # Produces a .ply that can be opened with the Gaussian Splatting Blender add-on"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "4D Gaussian Splatting: Dynamic Scenes"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "4D Gaussian Splatting (Wu et al. 2024) extends 3DGS to monocular video of dynamic scenes. Each Gaussian is given a "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "deformation field"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " that predicts how its position, rotation, and scale change as a function of time. The canonical Gaussians are kept in memory; at each frame, a lightweight MLP transforms them into the observed pose."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import torch\nimport torch.nn as nn\n\n\nclass GaussianDeformationField(nn.Module):\n    \"\"\"\n    Predicts per-Gaussian deltas (Δμ, Δq, Δs) from canonical position and time.\n    \"\"\"\n    def __init__(self, hidden: int = 64, n_freqs_t: int = 4, n_freqs_x: int = 6):\n        super().__init__()\n        in_dim = 3 + 3 * 2 * n_freqs_x + 1 + 1 * 2 * n_freqs_t\n        self.net = nn.Sequential(\n            nn.Linear(in_dim, hidden), nn.ReLU(),\n            nn.Linear(hidden, hidden), nn.ReLU(),\n            nn.Linear(hidden, hidden), nn.ReLU(),\n            nn.Linear(hidden, 3 + 4 + 3),   # Δpos + Δquat + Δscale\n        )\n        self.n_freqs_x, self.n_freqs_t = n_freqs_x, n_freqs_t\n\n    def forward(self, means: torch.Tensor, t: float) -> dict:\n        # means: (N, 3)  t: scalar in [0,1]\n        N = len(means)\n        t_tensor = torch.full((N, 1), t, device=means.device)\n\n        # Fourier features\n        pe_x = positional_encoding(means, self.n_freqs_x)       # (N, 3*2*L)\n        pe_t = positional_encoding(t_tensor, self.n_freqs_t)    # (N, 1*2*L)\n        h = torch.cat([means, pe_x, t_tensor, pe_t], dim=-1)\n\n        out = self.net(h)                               # (N, 10)\n        return {\n            \"delta_means\": out[:, :3],                  # position offset\n            \"delta_quats\": out[:, 3:7],                 # rotation offset\n            \"delta_scales\": out[:, 7:],                 # scale offset\n        }\n\n\ndef render_4dgs_frame(\n    canonical_scene: GaussianScene,\n    deform_net: GaussianDeformationField,\n    t: float,\n    viewmat: torch.Tensor,\n    K: torch.Tensor,\n    W: int, H: int,\n) -> torch.Tensor:\n    deltas = deform_net(canonical_scene.means, t)\n    deformed_means  = canonical_scene.means  + deltas[\"delta_means\"]\n    deformed_quats  = canonical_scene.quats  + deltas[\"delta_quats\"]\n    deformed_scales = canonical_scene.scales + deltas[\"delta_scales\"]\n\n    renders, _, _ = rasterization(\n        means     = deformed_means,\n        quats     = torch.nn.functional.normalize(deformed_quats, dim=-1),\n        scales    = torch.exp(deformed_scales),\n        opacities = torch.sigmoid(canonical_scene.opacities),\n        colors    = canonical_scene.sh_coeffs,\n        viewmats  = viewmat.unsqueeze(0),\n        Ks        = K.unsqueeze(0),\n        width=W, height=H,\n    )\n    return renders[0]   # (H, W, 3)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Converting Gaussians to Mesh: SuGaR and GOF"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "3DGS is not directly mesh-compatible — Gaussians are volumetric blobs, not surfaces. Two methods convert them:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "SuGaR (Surface Gaussian Reconstruction)."
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " Regularises training so Gaussians align flat against the surface (thin pancakes). After training, samples a point cloud from the flattened Gaussians and runs Poisson surface reconstruction to extract a triangle mesh. A second stage then binds a mesh to the Gaussians for texture baking."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Gaussian Opacity Fields (GOF)."
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " Defines a volumetric opacity field from the Gaussians and extracts a surface mesh using marching cubes at the iso-surface where opacity = 0.5, giving cleaner geometry than SuGaR for complex shapes."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "bash"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# SuGaR: two-stage conversion from a trained 3DGS scene\n# pip install sugar-scene\n\n# Stage 1: regularised 3DGS training\npython train.py -s ./scene/ -m output/scene --lambda_normal 0.05\n\n# Stage 2: extract mesh from flat Gaussians\npython extract_mesh.py \\\n  --scene_path output/scene \\\n  --iteration 30000 \\\n  --gaussians_in_all_cells     # use all Gaussians for denser mesh\n  # → output/scene/coarse_mesh.obj\n\n# Stage 3: bind and refine with texture\npython refine.py \\\n  --scene_path output/scene \\\n  --mesh_path output/scene/coarse_mesh.obj \\\n  --n_vertices_in_mesh 1000000\n  # → output/scene/refined_mesh.obj + texture PNG"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Practical Considerations"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "table",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "tableRow",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "tableHeader",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "paragraph",
