            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "tableRow",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "tableCell",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "paragraph",
                    "content": [
                      {
                        "type": "text",
                        "marks": [
                          {
                            "type": "bold"
                          }
                        ],
                        "text": "GPU memory"
                      }
                    ]
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "type": "tableCell",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "paragraph",
                    "content": [
                      {
                        "type": "text",
                        "text": "3–6 million Gaussians × 59 floats ≈ 0.7–1.4 GB GPU for scene parameters. Add 1–2 GB for the rasterizer tile buffers."
                      }
                    ]
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "tableRow",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "tableCell",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "paragraph",
                    "content": [
                      {
                        "type": "text",
                        "marks": [
                          {
                            "type": "bold"
                          }
                        ],
                        "text": "Capture quality"
                      }
                    ]
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "type": "tableCell",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "paragraph",
                    "content": [
                      {
                        "type": "text",
                        "text": "3DGS relies on a good COLMAP initialisation. Sparse, reflective, or textureless scenes cause missing Gaussians that adaptive density control cannot recover."
                      }
                    ]
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "tableRow",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "tableCell",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "paragraph",
                    "content": [
                      {
                        "type": "text",
                        "marks": [
                          {
                            "type": "bold"
                          }
                        ],
                        "text": "View extrapolation"
                      }
                    ]
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "type": "tableCell",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "paragraph",
                    "content": [
                      {
                        "type": "text",
                        "text": "Gaussians only populate regions observed during training. Novel views too far from the training distribution show floaters or holes — unlike NeRF which can sometimes extrapolate via the implicit representation."
                      }
                    ]
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "tableRow",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "tableCell",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "paragraph",
                    "content": [
                      {
                        "type": "text",
                        "marks": [
                          {
                            "type": "bold"
                          }
                        ],
                        "text": "PLY portability"
                      }
                    ]
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "type": "tableCell",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "paragraph",
                    "content": [
                      {
                        "type": "text",
                        "text": "The exported .ply can be loaded in Blender (add-on), Unity (URP), Unreal Engine, and Three.js via community rasterizers. The format is an open standard."
                      }
                    ]
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "tableRow",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "tableCell",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "paragraph",
                    "content": [
                      {
                        "type": "text",
                        "marks": [
                          {
                            "type": "bold"
                          }
                        ],
                        "text": "File size"
                      }
                    ]
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "type": "tableCell",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "paragraph",
                    "content": [
                      {
                        "type": "text",
                        "text": "A typical indoor scene PLY is 150–400 MB uncompressed. Compact3D and compressed-3DGS reduce this 10–20× with quantisation, making browser delivery practical."
                      }
                    ]
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Key Takeaways"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "3DGS achieves real-time novel-view synthesis (100–200 fps) by replacing ray-marching through an MLP with tile-based rasterisation of explicit 3D Gaussian blobs."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Gaussians are parameterised via rotation quaternion + scale vector to guarantee a valid covariance matrix throughout gradient descent."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Adaptive density control (clone / split / prune / opacity-reset) is what turns a sparse COLMAP point cloud into a dense, accurate reconstruction — the gradient-descent alone is insufficient."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "4D Gaussian Splatting adds a time-conditioned deformation field on top of canonical Gaussians — enabling real-time rendering of dynamic monocular video."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "SuGaR and GOF bridge 3DGS and traditional mesh pipelines by extracting a triangle mesh from the trained Gaussians, enabling downstream use in game engines and 3D printing."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "3DGS is now the default choice for interactive applications where NeRF's frame-per-minute rendering is impractical. NeRF remains superior for unbounded or poorly-captured scenes where an implicit prior helps."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
}
